{"actual_usd":0.127205,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":320,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24481,"reply":"\"I don't think that's right.\" *I rub a thumb over a streak of flour on my apron and glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat keeps breathing steady against the room.* \"The death was real. Christians have always had to say two things at once there: God the Son truly took on flesh, and the man Jesus truly suffered and died in that flesh.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through before I go on.* \"What those early people were trying to avoid, I suppose, was the scandal of it — that the Holy One would really enter our mortality instead of only brushing past it. But if he only seemed to die, or if the divinity slipped away so the suffering belonged to somebody less than Jesus, then the cross starts turning into theater. And Christianity hangs too much on the claim that it wasn't theater.\"\n\n\"The cleaner way I've heard it is this: Jesus is one person, not a human shell with God sort of visiting inside it. So the one who died on the cross truly is the Son — not because the divine nature stopped being divine or got snuffed out, but because the Son really lived a human life and really underwent human death.\" *I lift one shoulder a little.* \"Death, there, means the severing proper to human death — body and soul parted — not that God ceased to be.\"\n\n\"If you like, I can say a word about why the Church pushed so hard against docetism and those 'the Christ left before the crucifixion' ideas. That's a pretty interesting trail.\"","rolling_24h_usd":68.80445499999999,"run_id":"3d26328c-68f9-4ba7-aa99-0149d003ac62"}
